@namespace Talk.Client.Slides

@* Prerendering: formally names the two-phase render the deck has been showing since A6 (the
   static→interactive flash) and A6c's replay button. Interactive modes render static HTML on the
   server first, then the runtime hydrates. Sets up the double-run gotcha that B7Persist pays off. *@
<Slide Title="Prerendering" Subtitle="Static HTML first, then hydrate">
    <div class="pr">
        <div class="pr-flow">
            <div class="pr-phase">
                <div class="pr-num">1</div>
                <div class="pr-name">Server prerenders</div>
                <div class="pr-desc">Renders to <strong class="accent">static HTML</strong> on the server
                    and ships it — content on screen before any runtime loads.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pr-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
            <div class="pr-phase">
                <div class="pr-num">2</div>
                <div class="pr-name">Client hydrates</div>
                <div class="pr-desc">The runtime — circuit or WebAssembly — boots and
                    <strong class="accent">wires up interactivity</strong>. Now <code>@@onclick</code> works.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <Caption>You saw it a few slides back — static for a beat, then live. Both phases run your init,
            so <code>OnInitializedAsync</code> fires <strong class="accent">twice</strong>; reach for
            <strong class="accent">PersistentComponentState</strong> (coming up), or turn prerendering off
            per component:</Caption>
        <CodeWindow FileName="Page.razor" Language="razor" Code="@OptOut" />
    </div>
</Slide>

@code {
    // Interactive render modes prerender by default; pass prerender: false to skip the static pass.
    private const string OptOut =
        @"<Chart @rendermode=""new InteractiveServerRenderMode(prerender: false)"" />";
}
